        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose ALMA observations using Band 6 and the C34-3 configuration to obtain dust continuum and spectral line emission simultaneously. Band 6 and the C34-3 configuration offer a perfect match between the size of the target and the field of view of ALMA, and between the source structure and the angular resolution.

Requested sensitivity:
We aim at detecting line emission from complex organic molecules CH3OH and CH3CN for intermediate mass protostars at the distance of G11.11. The template spectra we base on is from an intermediate mass protostar IRAS22198 (Sanchez-Monge et al. 2010). After properly scaled to the distance of G11.11, we find a peak line flux of &gt; 15 mJy. We require a spectral line sensitivity of 2 mJy per 0.976 MHz resolution to yield a S/N of &gt; 7 for chemical studies. The H2CO line emission is these cold cores are brighter than 100 mJy, thus will be imaged with high S/N for kinematic studies. This continuum sensitivity should reach 0.03 mJy, assuming a bandwidth of 4 GHz of spectral line free channels. 

Correlator setup: 
To maximize the continuum sensitivity, we will configure the ALMA correlator in 4 spectral bands and dual polarization, with three base bands in 1.875 GHz bandwidth and a 488.3 kHz channel spacing (a spectral resolution of 976.6 KHz with Hanning smoothing), and one window using 234 MHz and 60 kHz channel spacing. The lower spectral resolution bands will cover SiO, CH3OH and CH3CN lines that are associated with protostellar outflow or hot molecular cores, which are in general broader line width. The high spectral resolution window will adequately resolve the N2D+ 3-2 and 13CS 5-4 transitions. One of the goals of the proposal is to investigate chemistry in cold cores. Therefore, we request data to be taken in full spectral resolution, which results in a high data rate.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
