    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Recent studies suggest that massive stars form in cold cores (&lt;~ 20K) embedded in massive infrared dark clouds with typical masses of 10^3 Msun. As a result of protostellar heating, cold cores evolve to warm (~50K) and hot molecular cores (&gt;100K) characterized by profuse line emission of complex organic molecules. Regions at the evolutionary phases of warm and hot molecular cores have been studied extensively. However, very little is known about the physical and chemical state of the cold core phase and their evolution due to a lack of sensitivity. We take advantage of the sensitivity of ALMA to follow on a set of cold cores in IRDC G11.11-0.12 uncovered in our SMA observations. The main goal is to detected spectral line emission at a spatial resolution better than the Jean length to study the initial fragmentation and chemical properties of cold molecular cores. By comparing with spectral lines data for warm and hot molecular cores already obtained with the SMA, we will investigate the evolution of protostellar accretion and chemistry of massive star formation.</prp:abstract>
